Explanation of reasoning and sources:

- I inspected app/Http/Controllers/Api/V1/PostController.php. The update method returns a PostResource on success and calls $this->authorize('update', $post). The PostResource (app/Http/Resources/Post.php) defines the JSON shape returned for a Post (id, title, slug, content, posted_at (ISO8601 string), author_id, comments_count, thumbnail_url and thumb_thumbnail_url when present). The controller will return this resource wrapped under the standard Laravel resource top-level "data" key.

- Validation for update is performed by App\Http\Requests\Admin\PostsRequest (app/Http/Requests/Admin/PostsRequest.php). Validation failures in Laravel return a 422 Unprocessable Entity and a standard Laravel JSON body: { "message": "The given data was invalid.", "errors": { "field": ["msg"] } }.

- Authorization failures (from $this->authorize) produce a 403 Forbidden and the tests assert the JSON: { "message": "This action is unauthorized." }.

- If the requested Post model doesn't exist, Laravel throws a ModelNotFoundException and the tests assert the JSON: { "message": "No query results for model [App\\Models\\Post] {id}" } — this corresponds to a 404 Not Found response.

- The update route is under the authenticated middleware in routes/api.php (auth:sanctum, verified). If the caller is unauthenticated, the API will return a 401 Unauthenticated response, typically with { "message": "Unauthenticated." }.

- Based on the above, relevant HTTP responses for PUT /v1/posts/{post} are:
  - 200: success — returns the updated Post resource (wrapped in "data").
  - 401: unauthenticated — message string.
  - 403: forbidden/unauthorized — message string (tests check this).
  - 404: not found — message string (tests check this).
  - 422: validation failed — message and errors object (standard Laravel structure).

- I constructed Swagger 2.0-style Response Objects (no $ref), using the concrete fields present in the PostResource. For optional fields (thumbnail URLs) I left them as non-required properties so they may be omitted. The 200 schema models the top-level resource envelope ("data") and the Post attributes. Error schemas model the JSON structures observed in controller/tests.

